  "diary": "Started the day with my usual ritual—coffee, stretches, breathing work in the quiet of my Eastlake place. The transit strike threw a wrench in things, so I drove to First Hill instead of taking the Link. The morning class felt good, bodies moving with intention despite the chaos outside. Grabbed tea between sessions and got lost reviewing camera specs for a bit—my mind needed the break. Led a solid wellness coaching session, then walked over to Voula's for a simple lunch. The afternoon class had decent energy. Once transit came back online at 4pm, I headed home early to beat the rideshare surge pricing. Spent the late afternoon painting in my studio, chasing that golden light coming through the windows. Something about the day's disruption made me slower, more deliberate. Made a light dinner, journaled a bit, then spent the evening with a book and my camera. Ended the day feeling grounded, like I'd actually lived it instead of just moving through it.",
  "thought_process": "The transit strike initially felt like an inconvenience—I had to drive instead of my usual routine—but it actually worked in my favor. Getting to First Hill early gave me buffer time, and I taught with less mental friction than usual. I stayed present through the classes because there was no option to rush. My break with the camera gear was pure indulgence, and I didn't feel guilty about it because the morning had been solid. The decision to head home before 4pm was practical (surge pricing), but it also felt like the universe giving me permission to stop early. My creative work in the studio afterward felt earned, unhurried. I think disruption to routine sometimes reveals what I actually want versus what I'm just defaulting to. Today reminded me why I chose this life—flexibility, presence, the ability to paint in afternoon light.",
